## 🏗️ Detailed Architecture & Components I Built

**Hypervisor**: VirtualBox (with snapshots enabled)  
**Firewall**: pfSense 2.7+ (multi-interface, VLAN capable)  
**Domain**: Windows Server 2022 Domain Controller with organisational units and basic GPOs  
**Vulnerable Targets**: Metasploitable 2/3 + DVWA web app  
**Clients**: Windows 10/11 domain-joined  
**Attacker**: Kali Linux (full tool suite)  
**Monitoring**: Wazuh agent deployment started  

**Key Learnings from the Practical Work So Far**:

- **Segmentation is everything**. Simply putting machines on different virtual networks dramatically reduces blast radius — I immediately saw how a compromise in the DMZ could be contained from the internal AD domain. This is exactly how Defence networks are protected.

- **Firewall rule writing is strategic**. Crafting rules that allow only specific traffic (e.g. AD ports 389/445 only from internal subnet) forced me to think like a defender. I learnt how overly permissive rules create the attack paths red-teamers love.

- **Active Directory introduces real complexity and risk**. Setting up the DC and joining machines taught me how Group Policy can enforce Essential Eight controls at scale, but also how a single weak account becomes a high-value target.

- **Documentation discipline matters**. Writing detailed justifications while building made me realise how officers must be able to explain their defensive designs to non-technical leadership.

- **Tool familiarity accelerates**. Configuring pfSense interfaces and rules took less time than expected because I had researched thoroughly first — showing the power of preparation before hands-on work.

